        [Insert Video]  
      </HorSection2>

      <HorSection2
        title="What is a Derivative?"
        id="Derivative_Definition"
        direction="left"
        fontsize1="4rem"
        fontsize2="2rem"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        width="100%"
      >
        <strong>Definition:</strong><br>
      &nbsp;&nbsp;A derivative measures the <strong>rate of change</strong> of a function with respect to a variable.<br>
      &nbsp;&nbsp;In simpler words: It tells us how <strong>fast something is changing</strong> at a specific point.<br><br>

        <div id ="Derivative_Concept" ></div>
        <Accordion
        title="Concept Explanation"
        id="ConceptExplanation1"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        <strong>Concept Explanation:</strong><br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;Imagine a car moving on a road. The position of the car depends on time.<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;If we ask: <strong>“How fast is the car moving at exactly 5 seconds?”</strong><br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;That <strong>instant speed</strong> is the derivative.<br><br>

        &nbsp;&nbsp;So:<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;• Position → derivative = Velocity<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;• Velocity → derivative = Acceleration<br><br>
        </Accordion>

        <div id ="Derivative_Visual" ></div>
        <Accordion
        title="Visual Explanation"
        id="VisualExplanation1"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        <strong>Visual Concept:</strong><br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;The derivative is the <strong>slope of the tangent line</strong> to a curve at a specific point.<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;• Secant line → average change<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;• Tangent line → instantaneous change<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;As two points get closer together, the secant line becomes the tangent line.<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;That <strong>limiting process</strong> is what defines a derivative.
        </Accordion>
      </HorSection2>

      <HorSection2
        title="Derivative Rules"
        id="Derivative_Rules"
        direction="left"
        fontsize1="4rem"
        fontsize2="2rem"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        width="100%"
      >
        <h3>Why Do We Need Derivative Rules?</h3>
    The derivative comes from <strong>limits</strong>, which can be long and complicated.<br>
    Instead of solving limits every time, mathematicians developed <strong>rules</strong> that make differentiation <strong>fast and systematic</strong>.<br><br>

        <Accordion
        title="A. Constant Rule: (Click to View)"
        id="A. Constant Rule"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        &nbsp;&nbsp;Concept: A constant does not change. No change → <strong>zero rate of change</strong>.<br>
        <strong>Equation:</strong> d/dx [c] = 0<br><br>
        </Accordion>
        
        <Accordion
        title="B. Power Rule: (Click to View)"
        id="B. Power Rule"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        &nbsp;&nbsp;Concept: The exponent controls how fast the function grows. The derivative shows how steep the curve becomes.<br>
<strong>Equation:</strong> d/dx [xⁿ] = n·xⁿ⁻¹<br><br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;Why it works: When you apply the <strong>limit definition</strong> to powers of x, this pattern always appears.<br><br>
        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="C. Sum and Difference Rules: (Click to View)"
        id="C. Sum and Difference Rules"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        &nbsp;&nbsp;Concept: If two functions are added or subtracted, their <strong>rates of change</strong> also add or subtract.<br>
<strong>Equation:</strong> (f + g)' = f' + g'<br><br>

        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="D. Constant Multiple Rule: (Click to View)"
        id="D. Constant Multiple Rule"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        &nbsp;&nbsp;Concept: If a function is stretched vertically by a constant, its slope is also stretched by that same constant.<br>
<strong>Equation:</strong> (c·f)' = c·f'<br><br>

        </Accordion>
        
        <Accordion
        title="E. Product Rule: (Click to View)"
        id="E. Product Rule"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        
&nbsp;&nbsp;Concept: When two functions multiply, both are changing.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;Equation: <strong>(uv)' = uv' + vu'</strong><br><br>

        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="F. Quotient Rule: (Click to View)"
        id="F. Quotient Rule"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        &nbsp;&nbsp;Concept: When dividing two changing functions, both the numerator and denominator affect the rate of change.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;Equation: <strong>(u/v)' = (vu' − uv') / v²</strong><br><br>

        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="G. Chain Rule: (Click to View)"
        id="G. Chain Rule"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        &nbsp;&nbsp;Concept: Used when a function is inside another function.<br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;Example:<br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Outer function: (something)⁵<br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Inner function: 3x + 1<br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;Equation: <strong>d/dx [f(g(x))] = f'(g(x))·g'(x)</strong>

        </Accordion>

      </HorSection2>

      <HorSection2
        title="What is a Derivative?"
        id="Derivative_Definition"
        direction="left"
        fontsize1="4rem"
        fontsize2="2rem"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        width="100%"
      >
        <strong>Definition:</strong><br>
      &nbsp;&nbsp;A derivative measures the <strong>rate of change</strong> of a function with respect to a variable.<br>
      &nbsp;&nbsp;In simpler words: It tells us how <strong>fast something is changing</strong> at a specific point.<br><br>


        <Accordion
        title="Concept Explanation"
        id="ConceptExplanation"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        <strong>Concept Explanation:</strong><br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;Imagine a car moving on a road. The position of the car depends on time.<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;If we ask: <strong>“How fast is the car moving at exactly 5 seconds?”</strong><br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;That <strong>instant speed</strong> is the derivative.<br><br>

        &nbsp;&nbsp;So:<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;• Position → derivative = Velocity<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;• Velocity → derivative = Acceleration<br><br>
        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="Visual Explanation"
        id="VisualExplanation"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        <strong>Visual Concept:</strong><br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;The derivative is the <strong>slope of the tangent line</strong> to a curve at a specific point.<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;• Secant line → average change<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;• Tangent line → instantaneous change<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;As two points get closer together, the secant line becomes the tangent line.<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;That <strong>limiting process</strong> is what defines a derivative.
        </Accordion>
      </HorSection2>

      <HorSection2
        title="Examples"
        id="Derivative_Examples"
        direction="left"
        fontsize1="4rem"
        fontsize2="2rem"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        width="100%"
      >
        ll derivative rules are based on <strong>one key idea</strong>:<br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;How does a <strong>small change in x</strong> affect the function?<br><br>

    &nbsp;&nbsp;If:<br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;• The function <strong>increases</strong> → the derivative is <strong>positive</strong>.<br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;• The function <strong>decreases</strong> → the derivative is <strong>negative</strong>.<br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;• The function is <strong>flat</strong> → the derivative is <strong>zero</strong>.<br><br>

        <Accordion
        title="Real-Life Applications"
        id="DE_IRL"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        Derivatives are used in many real-world fields:<br><br>

    <strong>Economics:</strong><br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;Used to analyze <strong>marginal cost</strong> and <strong>profit maximization</strong>.<br><br>

    <strong>Physics:</strong><br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;Used to find <strong>velocity</strong> and <strong>acceleration</strong> from position functions.<br><br>

    <strong>Engineering:</strong><br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;Used in <strong>optimization problems</strong> such as designing efficient systems or structures.<br><br>

    <strong>Biology:</strong><br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;Used to model <strong>population growth rates</strong> and changes in ecosystems.<br><br>

    <strong>Machine Learning:</strong><br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;Used in algorithms like <strong>gradient descent</strong> to minimize errors in models.<br><br>
        </Accordion>

      </HorSection2>

      <HorSection2
title="Made with ❤ from Scalable!"
direction="left"
fontsize1="1rem"
fontsize2="1rem"
